---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Terminal from "../components/Terminal.astro";
import Skill from "../components/Skill.astro";
import PairMarker from "../components/PairMarker.astro";
import { SKILLS } from "../data/skills";

const setupPrompt = `Set up this repo to use srid/agency by following the instructions at
https://github.com/srid/agency/blob/master/docs/agency-setup.md`;

const year = new Date().getFullYear();
---

<BaseLayout title="agency">
  <header class="topbar">
    <span class="topbar-mark">srid<span class="slash">/</span>agency</span>
    <a href="https://github.com/srid/agency" rel="noopener">github ↗</a>
  </header>

  <section class="hero wrap">
    <h1 class="hero-mark">agency<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
    <p class="hero-eyebrow">a workflow for coding agents</p>

    <p class="hero-slogan">
      a loop you can<br />
      <span class="accent-magenta">leave alone.</span>
    </p>

    <p class="hero-tag">
      Two skills. <Skill name="talk" /> for design. <Skill name="do" /> for
      shipping. End-to-end, every diff.
    </p>

    <Terminal text={setupPrompt} />
  </section>

  <section class="sec wrap">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-num">01</span>
      <div>
        <p class="sec-label">the loop</p>
        <h2 class="h2">
          <Skill name="talk" as="span" /> to design,
          <Skill name="do" as="span" /> to ship.
        </h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pair">
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <PairMarker name="talk" suffix="spec isn't obvious" />
        <p class="pair-headline">Sketch first. Ship later.</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          Discuss, read, sketch. Run <Skill name="hickey" /> +
          <Skill name="lowy" /> on the sketch. Read-only. Hand the converged
          plan to <Skill name="do" />.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <PairMarker name="do" suffix={'"done" is concrete'} />
        <p class="pair-headline">Research → review → ship.</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          Implement. Run <Skill name="hickey" /> + <Skill name="lowy" /> +
          <Skill name="code-police" /> on the diff. CI, merge. Each fix lands
          as its own commit.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="body" style="margin-top: 2.25rem;">
      <p>
        <strong><Skill name="do" /> has no design phase.</strong> Pasting a
        thin plan into <Skill name="do" /> produces a thin implementation. The
        fix is to do the design work in <Skill name="talk" /> first.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="sec wrap">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-num">02</span>
      <div>
        <p class="sec-label">feedback</p>
        <h2 class="h2">no signal, <span class="accent-cyan">no loop.</span></h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="body" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <p>
        The agent needs a signal that its change actually worked. Unit tests
        and type-checks alone don't give it; what does depends on the surface.
      </p>
    </div>

    <ul class="triple" style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
      <li class="triple-cell is-magenta">
        <p class="triple-label">frontend</p>
        <p class="triple-body">
          Screenshot evidence on every PR —
          <a
            href="https://github.com/juspay/kolu/pull/791#issuecomment-4352641175"
            rel="noopener">like kolu#791</a
          >.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="triple-cell is-cyan">
        <p class="triple-label">nix infra</p>
        <p class="triple-body">
          NixOS VM tests. Closest thing to an executable spec the agent can
          drive.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="triple-cell is-lime">
        <p class="triple-label">backend / library</p>
        <p class="triple-body">
          Fast, deterministic e2e. 30s deterministic beats 10min thorough.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="sec wrap">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-num">03</span>
      <div>
        <p class="sec-label">structural review</p>
        <h2 class="h2">
          complexity hides in
          <span style={`color: ${SKILLS.hickey.color}`}>space</span>
          and in
          <span style={`color: ${SKILLS.lowy.color}`}>time</span>.
        </h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="body" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <p>
        After implementing, <Skill name="do" /> runs <Skill name="hickey" /> +
        <Skill name="lowy" /> in parallel against the actual diff. Each
        finding lands as its own commit; the full ledger ships as a PR
        comment.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="pair">
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <PairMarker name="hickey" suffix="the space lens" />
        <p class="pair-headline">Is anything complected here?</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          After Rich Hickey's <em>Simple Made Easy</em>. Flags two ideas
          braided into one construct — the kind of complecting that tests
          pass straight through.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <PairMarker name="lowy" suffix="the time lens" />
        <p class="pair-headline">What changes at a different rate?</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          After Juval Lowy's <em>Righting Software</em>. Flags modules
          coupled to neighbours that drift on a different schedule —
          volatility time-bombs that won't surface until later.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="body" style="margin-top: 2.25rem;">
      <p>
        Full framing:
        <a href="https://kolu.dev/blog/hickey-lowy/" rel="noopener">Hickey/Lowy on kolu.dev</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="sec wrap">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-num">04</span>
      <div>
        <p class="sec-label">project rules</p>
        <h2 class="h2">your codebase. <span class="accent-magenta">your rules.</span></h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="body" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <p>
        Drop a <code>.agency/&lt;skill&gt;.md</code> file at the repo root and
        the matching skill picks it up — plain Markdown, opt-in, no APM
        ceremony. Adopt skills à la carte; layer your own rules on top of the
        built-ins.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="pair">
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <PairMarker name="code-police" />
        <p class="pair-headline">Your quality gate, your rules.</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          <code>.agency/code-police.md</code> layers project-specific rules
          on top of the built-in checklist — &ldquo;never use
          <code>as any</code>&rdquo;, &ldquo;always use TanStack Query for
          fetches&rdquo;, whatever your codebase needs. Enforced on every
          <Skill name="do" /> diff.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pair-cell">
        <p class="pair-marker">
          <Skill name="hickey" />, <Skill name="lowy" />, <Skill name="do" />
        </p>
        <p class="pair-headline">Same pattern, opt-in.</p>
        <p class="pair-body">
          <code>.agency/hickey.md</code> + <code>.agency/lowy.md</code>
          declare project-specific complecting patterns and axes of
          volatility. <code>.agency/do.md</code> declares your
          <code>check</code> / <code>test</code> / <code>ci</code> commands and
          an opt-in <code>## PR evidence</code> step.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="foot wrap">
    <p class="colophon">
      <a href="https://github.com/srid/agency" rel="noopener"
        >github.com/srid/agency</a
      >
      <span>·</span>
      <a href="https://kolu.dev" rel="noopener">sister · kolu.dev</a>
      <span>·</span>
      <span>mit · {year}</span>
    </p>
  </footer>
</BaseLayout>
